        "clue": "Explain how the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution acted as a blank check, how containment and domino theory drove troop increases, and how the Tet Offensive shocked military leaders into asking for more troops.",
        "answer": "“One reason why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 was the political authorization granted by the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution in August 1964.” After alleged clashes between the destroyer [[USS Maddox]] and North Vietnamese patrol boats, Congress passed the resolution giving President Johnson a 'blank check' to deploy combat troops without a formal declaration of war. {{Therefore, the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution was a vital cause of why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 because it removed legislative barriers, allowing the deployment of Marines to Da Nang in March 1965.}}\n\n“A second reason why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 was the strategic commitment to the Cold War policy of containment and the Domino Theory.” US military planners believed that if South Vietnam fell to communism, neighboring nations like Laos and Cambodia would fall next. To prevent this, General Westmoreland implemented [[search-and-destroy]] missions, raising troop levels to [[535,000]] by 1968. {{Therefore, the geopolitical policy of containment was a fundamental reason why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 because it made stopping communism in South Vietnam a top national security priority.}}\n\n“A third reason why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 was the strategic crisis and loss of control caused by the Tet Offensive in early 1968.” The Vietcong launched a massive surprise attack on over 100 cities, including the US Embassy in Saigon. Though militarily defeated, the [[Tet Offensive]] shattered US claims of imminent victory and led to requests for [[206,000]] more troops. {{Therefore, the military shock of the Tet Offensive was a decisive reason why US military involvement in Vietnam escalated in the years 1964–68 because it proved current force levels were failing, forcing a choice between withdrawal or further escalation.}}"
