        "clue": "Focus on working-class patriotism and fear of communism, Nixon's political appeals to the Silent Majority, and the class resentment toward draft-exempt student protesters.",
        "answer": "“One reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 was their deep-seated patriotism and fear of communist expansion.” Many conservative and working-class citizens believed that a communist victory in South Vietnam would damage US global credibility. They accepted the [[Domino Theory]] and argued that abandoning an ally would lead to a communist bloodbath. {{Therefore, anti-communist patriotism was a key reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 because they viewed the conflict as a necessary stand against global communism.}}\n\n“A second reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 was President Nixon's successful political mobilization of the Silent Majority.” In his November 1969 speech, Nixon called on the quiet, law-abiding majority of Americans to support his policy of [[Vietnamisation]]. This speech gave a voice to patriotic citizens, presenting them as the moral backbone of the country against radicals. {{Therefore, Nixon's political appeal to the Silent Majority was a crucial reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 because it framed support for his policies as a patriotic duty.}}\n\n“A third reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 was class resentment against middle-class student anti-war protesters.” Working-class families, whose drafted sons did not have college deferments, saw student demonstrators as privileged, unpatriotic draft-dodgers who insulted the military. This division led to pro-war events like the [[Hard Hat Riots]] of 1970. {{Therefore, working-class resentment of student protesters was a major reason why some Americans supported US involvement in the Vietnam War in the years 1969–72 because it aligned patriotic sentiment against the anti-war movement.}}"
